data.content:
Yes, the arguments are swapped. In MSTest, `Assert.AreEqual` signature is:

```
Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual)
```

Your code puts `result` (actual) first and the literal (expected) second. Here's the fix:

```csharp
// Before (wrong order)
Assert.AreEqual(result, 5);
Assert.AreEqual(result, 0);

// After (correct order)
Assert.AreEqual(5, result);
Assert.AreEqual(0, result);
```

This matters because when a test fails, MSTest uses parameter order to report **"Expected: X, Actual: Y"** — swapped arguments produce confusing failure messages.
